'''Tsukuridashi''' (造出) refers to semicircular or rectangular platform-like facilities attached directly to ancient Japanese tombs (kofun). It is also written as "Tsukuridashi" or "Tsuridashi" and is observed in only a small number of kofun, primarily mid-to-late period large-scale {{ill|Keyhole-shaped tumuli|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. {{右|[[File:ZenpokoenfunMoshikizu.svg|thumb|220px|right|Diagram of a {{ill|Keyhole-shaped tumuli|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}]]}}
== Overview ==
[[file:CG Danpusan Kofun from above 80m 7p.JPG|250px|thumb|right|{{ill|Danpusan Kofun|ja|断夫山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Nagoya|ja|名古屋市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, showing the tsukuridashi (center of the image).]] Tsukuridashi has been confirmed in keyhole-shaped tumuli, {{ill|Rectangular keyhole-shaped mounds|ja|前方後方墳|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Round tumuli|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Square tumuli|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, but it is predominantly found in keyhole-shaped tumuli. While large kofun often include tsukuridashi, some royal-level tombs, such as the {{ill|Hōraiyama Kofun|ja|宝来山古墳|1=Hōraiyama Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, lack them. Conversely, smaller kofun like the {{ill|Futazuka Kofun (Katsuragi)|ja|新庄二塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, measuring only 60 meters, include them. The criteria for including tsukuridashi remain unclear.
The function of tsukuridashi has been debated historically. Early theories include mimicry of wagon wheels (Gamō Kunpei), imitation of jar handles (Tadahiko Shimada), and burial spaces for sacrificial victims (Hiroshi Nishikawa). The widely accepted view today is that they were ritual spaces.<ref>Numazawa (2006), p. 283.</ref> It is believed that rituals performed on the Kofun were eventually relocated to the tsukuridashi.
== Development ==
